#import "common.typ": *

= Introduction <introduction>

Most #ndbd interactions in the CUORE detector are expected to be contained within a single crystal, and forms the basis for our main analysis. However, approximately 5% should deposit energy across adjacent crystals. This analysis isolates these dual-site events to constrain the #ndbd decay signature. Using the CUORE Background Model (BM) analysis with the 1 ton-yr data release as the starting point, we aim to extract a constraint on the #ndbd half-life based a Bayesian Markov Chain Monte Carlo optimization method. Focusing on coincident events suppresses expected backgrounds, yielding competitive relative sensitivity compared to the primary single-site constraint.

As discussed in @data the region of interest (ROI) for this analysis is a thin two-dimentional diagonal band in $(E_1, E_2)$, with sparse data. This creates a few unique challenges like partially inluded bins and regions where simulated events themselves are sparse, which we dwell into more detail in @fit_model. It also compares this restricted region to a background model constrained over a much wider energy range, making the residual differences in spectral shape more visible (Ex #Co60 sum peak). Furthermore, as the fit is built from simulated spectra rather than a fully analytic model, most nuisance effects cannot be incorporated in a purely closed-form way (refer to @systematics). @methods outlines analysis methods including the Bayesian Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methodology used to derive the #ndbd half-life posterior distribution, followed by @results that discusses the output from of the main fit.
